ce:section.ce:para:
Advanced oxidation processes (AOPs) based on the production and subsequent attack of hydroxyl (OH

                     ) radicals are considered as one of the promising ways for the treatment of wastewater containing biologically and chemically stable molecules [4]. Cavitation is also effective in treating the refractory pollutants based on hydroxyl (OH

                     ) radical attack coupled with local hot spots giving pyrolytic dissociation. Cavitation induced by the passage of ultrasound is described as acoustic cavitation and this approach has been applied widely for the degradation of biorefractory chemicals. Even though ultrasound has shown promise for oxidation of pollutants, most of the studies have been only at laboratory scale level. Hua and Hochemer [5] reported that ultrasound is an effective treatment approach for rapid destruction of organic contaminants based on the transformation of substrates like pesticides and chlorinated hydrocarbon into short-chain organic acids, CO2 and inorganic ions as the final products using a batch sonochemical reactor operating over the frequency range of 20–500kHz. Degradation of acephate using the ultrasound and ozone induced oxidation, operated individually and in combination was investigated by Wang et al. [6] and the combination of ultrasonic irradiation at 160kHz frequency with ozonation was reported to give enhanced degradation efficiency of 87.6%, which was about 30% higher as compared to only ultrasound.
